for labor migrants while simultaneously cracking down on illegal migration. Working in the crosshairs of debates surrounding national security and labor, officials have limited individual influence, few ties to each other, and no serious contact with the people whose movements they regulate. As Feldman reveals, this complex construction creates a world of indirect human relations that enables the violence of social indifference as much as the targeted brutality of collective hatred. Employing an innovative "nonlocal" ethnographic methodology, Feldman illuminates the danger of allowing indifference to govern how we regulate population-and people's lives-in the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aForeign workersxGovernment policyxEuropean Union countries. 0aForeign workersxGovernment policyzEuropean Union countries. 0aIllegal aliensxGovernment policyxEuropean Union countries. 0aIllegal aliensxGovernment policyzEuropean Union countries. 0aInternal securityxEuropean Union countries. 0aInternal securityzEuropean Union countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477912840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804779128.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles